# CODEOWNERS — per-file review ownership.
#
# How this works: when a PR modifies a file matched by a line below, the
# listed owner(s) are AUTO-REQUESTED as reviewers. If the branch ruleset has
# `require_code_owner_review` enabled, that owner's approval is REQUIRED
# before merge.
#
# Why no catch-all `*` line: with a single human + a code-author agent on
# this repo, requiring code-owner review on EVERY file would gate routine
# UI/code changes behind the second human's approval — that's the "go-
# between" bottleneck we explicitly want to avoid. So only the genuinely
# sensitive files get owners listed, and everything else can ship under
# the branch ruleset's status-check + no-force-push protection alone.
#
# GitHub rule: a PR author cannot approve their own PR. So files listed
# below CANNOT be merged via self-approval — they require @llamanftstaking-
# glitch to actively click approve. This is intentional friction; these
# files matter enough to be worth the round-trip wait.
#
# To remove someone from required reviewers temporarily: delete or comment
# out their handle on the relevant line and merge a quick PR (which can
# self-approve since it doesn't touch the listed files).
#
# Docs: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-security/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners

# ============================================================================
# Security & auth — anything touching the trust boundary
# ============================================================================

# Firestore rules govern who can read/write what in the production database.
# A buggy rules deploy could expose user data or break crowd-response writes
# for everyone. Always reviewed by both humans.
/firestore.rules                    @llamanftstaking-glitch

# Firebase config: API keys, project IDs, auth domain whitelist hints. Not
# secret per se (ships to browser) but mis-edits break auth for everyone.
/src/config.js                      @llamanftstaking-glitch

# ============================================================================
# Deploy infrastructure — anything CI/CD touches
# ============================================================================

# GH Actions workflows: the auto-deploy + preview-deploy machinery. A
# malicious or buggy workflow change could leak the Firebase service-account
# secret or deploy bogus content to production.
/.github/workflows/                 @llamanftstaking-glitch

# Firebase hosting config: which files get deployed, cache headers, ignore
# list. Mis-edits could deploy `firestore.rules` (no, the ignore list catches
# it) or break the cache invalidation that controls app version flips.
/firebase.json                      @llamanftstaking-glitch
/.firebaserc                        @llamanftstaking-glitch

# ============================================================================
# Legal & ownership boundary
# ============================================================================

# LICENSE: governs what others can do with the code. Don't change without
# both humans signing off.
/LICENSE                            @llamanftstaking-glitch

# CODEOWNERS itself: changing ownership rules should require approval from
# the people currently listed as owners. (GitHub enforces this automatically
# when CODEOWNERS lists itself.)
/.github/CODEOWNERS                 @llamanftstaking-glitch
